         <entryFree xml:id="k000256" type="architectural feature">
            <term xml:id="term-k000256-1" xml:lang="zh-latn-pinyin-nt" source="#biblk000256-1">dangong</term>
            <term xml:id="term-k000256-2" xml:lang="zh-Hant">單栱</term>
            <term xml:id="term-k000256-3" xml:lang="zh-Hans">单栱</term>
            <term xml:id="term-k000256-4" xml:lang="zh-latn-pinyin">dāngǒng</term>
            <term xml:id="term-k000256-5" xml:lang="zh-latn-wadegile" source="#biblk000257-2">tan-kung</term>
            <term xml:id="term-k000256-6" xml:lang="en">single arms (lit. ATTCAT 2023)</term>
            <idno type="URI">https://architecturasinica.org/keyword/k000256</idno>
            <note type="Note">
               <p xml:lang="en" source="#biblk000256-3">Literally “single bracket arms,” dangong are individual bracket arms placed parallel to the building plane that support squared beams (fang <term ref="/keyword/k000116">方</term>), as opposed to other bracket arms (compare to: chonggong <term ref="/keyword/k000257">重栱</term>). They are also constructed in the style called linggong <term ref="/keyword/k000156-3">令栱</term> in reference to their position and/or measurement. The practice of using only single bracket arms is called “dangongzao <term ref="/keyword/k000265">單栱造</term>.”  As an architectural term, we have only found dangong in Yingzao fashi and Siling lu (Zhou 1848, 173.11b). </p>
               <p xml:lang="zh-Hant" source="#biblk000256-3">單栱指平行於屋身方向的單層栱，其上承枋/<term ref="/keyword/k000116">方</term>。斗栱僅用單層橫栱的做法稱單栱造，所用橫栱採取<term ref="/keyword/k000156">令栱</term>的形式(李 2009,卷4,卷9)。與單栱相對的概念是重栱。作爲建築術語，在曆史文獻中已知僅見於《營造法式》及《思陵錄》（周必大 1848, 173.11b）。</p>
            </note>
            <note type="related concepts">
               <p><term ref="/keyword/k000257">重栱 chónggǒng</term></p>
               <p><term ref="/keyword/k000265">單栱造 dāngǒngzào</term></p>
               <p><term ref="/keyword/k000156">令栱 lìnggǒng</term></p>
               <p><term ref="/keyword/k000167">泥道栱 nídàogǒng </term></p>
            </note>
